IBM Data Science Capstone - week 4 assignment¶

Introduction, business problem and target audience¶

Florence offers an incredibly active nightlife scene. Locals love to enjoy the night and the city is full of artist, university students and tourist. This makes a very open and international environment with a unique reneissance historical athmosphere. There are quite a lot of different nightlife spots and they seem to do very well. A new business owner is planning to enter the market of nightlife venues of Florence. Most likely being able to attract walk-in customers is essential. This is necessary to keep the marketing and customer acquisition cost down and make the operation effective. The scope of this analysis is to identify the ideal location and the venue type which is most likely to draw in people. The target audience is anyone planning to open a new nightlife spot in Florence but haven't decided yet regarding the location and main profile of the place.

Data¶

In order to answer the question in hand we need the following data. First of all a list of venues in Florence. This is obtained from Foursqure API. I created a meshgrid of goegraphical coordinates over the city to page trough it. After that I had to deduplicated the list. This might seem like an unnecessary complication but it results in a more complete dataset. Also I had to obtain the boundaries of the city from OpenStreetMap Nominatim API and boundaries for each of its five districts as well. I used these polygons to sort each venue to the district where it is located. Neighborhood boundaries were not available but I managed to get the coordinates of the central point for each and sorted each venue to the neighborhood closest to it. In order to sort the venues to fewer and more meaningful categories I used the hierarchical tree of venue categories obtanied from Foursquare API. I also used the venue details endpoint of the Foursquare API to obtaine some details about each venue in the category that is most relevant in regard of the question. More specificly I got information about the venue price tier, number of likes, rating and number of tips for each venue in the Nightlife Spots category. I used a number of tools to acquire and manage the data, like Pandas and NumPy to handle the tables, request make calls to the different APIs, geopy in correspondence with Nominatim calls and also to measure distance, geometry the test if a venue is inside the city / a given district, math and sklearn the make transformations and scaling (I used log transformation to handle skewness, and built in routine to create dummy variables). The following table contains metadata about the dataset I used.

Data content Data Source Transformation and other processing Other info
Venue Name Foursquare API explore endpoint
Venue Latitude Foursquare API explore endpoint
Venue Longitude Foursquare API explore endpoint
Venue Category Foursquare API explore endpoint used to find compatitors and relevant market

def adr2ll(address):
    geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="my-capstone-app")
    a = geolocator.geocode(address)
    return [a.latitude, a.longitude]


# return a grid of coordinate paires
def lat_lng_meshgrid(city, radius=0.25):
    center = adr2ll(city)
    nx, ny = (120,120)
    x = np.linspace(center[0]-radius/3, center[0]+radius/3, nx)
    y = np.linspace(center[1]-radius/2, center[1]+radius/2, ny)
    xv, yv = np.meshgrid(x, y)
    xy = np.transpose([np.tile(x, len(y)), np.repeat(y, len(x))])
    return xy

grid = lat_lng_meshgrid("Florence")
grid_df = pd.DataFrame(grid)

# pre filter the grid (no foursquare api calls outside florence)

url_geojson = 'https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/search.php?q=Florence%2C%20Italy&polygon_geojson=1&format=geojson'
geojson = requests.get(url_geojson)
shp = shape(geojson.json()['features'][0]['geometry'])
polygon = Polygon(shp)
def gen(s):
    a = polygon.contains(Point(s[1],s[0]))
    return a

grid_df["isincity"] = grid_df.apply(gen, axis=1)
grid_df = grid_df.loc[grid_df.isincity, :]

This is the same function we used in the labs. The only modification I made is that in case the API fails to get a response I run it again.

def getNearbyVenues(latitudes, longitudes, radius=200):
    
    venues_list=[]
    for lat, lng in zip(latitudes, longitudes):

        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}&sortByDistance=1'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT)
            
        # make the GET request
        try:
            results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        # give it a second try in case it fails
        except:
            try:
                results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
            except:
                try:
                    results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
                except:
                    try:
                        results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
                    except:
                        try:
                            results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
                        except:
                            try:
                                results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
                            except:
                                results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue and only if city is known
        try:
            venues_list.append([(lat, 
                lng,
                v['venue']['name'],
                v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
                v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
                v['venue']['categories'][0]['name'],
                v['venue']['id']) for v in results])
        except:
            pass
            
    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['grid Latitude', 
                  'grid Longitude', 
                  'Venue',
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category',
                  'Venue ID']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

florence_venues = getNearbyVenues(  latitudes=grid_df[0],
                                   longitudes=grid_df[1]
                                  )

# remove duplicate venues
# in case of multiple occurrances keep the ones with the minimal distance from the grid point

def calc_dist_from_gridpoint(s):
    dist = geodesic((s['grid Latitude'], s['grid Longitude']), (s['Venue Latitude'], s['Venue Longitude'])).meters
    return(dist)
florence_venues['distance_from_grid_point'] = florence_venues.apply(calc_dist_from_gridpoint, axis=1)
florence_venues_deduplicated = florence_venues.sort_values(by='distance_from_grid_point').groupby(['Venue ID']).head(1).reset_index(drop=True)

def return_district(s):
    q1 = polygon_florence_q1.contains(Point(s['Venue Longitude'],s['Venue Latitude']))
    q2 = polygon_florence_q2.contains(Point(s['Venue Longitude'],s['Venue Latitude']))
    q3 = polygon_florence_q3.contains(Point(s['Venue Longitude'],s['Venue Latitude']))
    q4 = polygon_florence_q4.contains(Point(s['Venue Longitude'],s['Venue Latitude']))
    q5 = polygon_florence_q5.contains(Point(s['Venue Longitude'],s['Venue Latitude']))
    if q1:
        district="q1"
    elif q2:
        district="q2"
    elif q3:
        district="q3"
    elif q4:
        district="q4"
    elif q5:
        district="q5"    
    else:
        district="Not in Florence"
    return(district)

florence_venues_deduplicated['district']=florence_venues_deduplicated.apply(return_district,axis=1)
florence_venues_deduplicated = florence_venues_deduplicated.loc[florence_venues_deduplicated.district!="Not in Florence", :]

I pulled the hierarchy of venue categories from Foursquare. The business problem is about the ideal location and profile of a nighlife spot. I devided the list of venues to three part. First the competitors that other relevants venues and lastly the not relevant part.

In [8]:
# get venue categories hierachy
categories_url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/categories?client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET,
            VERSION)
categories = requests.get(categories_url)
x = categories.json()["response"]["categories"]
x[0]["categories"]

categories_hierarchy=[]

for level1item in x:
    a = level1item["name"]
    categories_hierarchy.append([a,a,a,a])
    b = level1item["categories"]
    for level2item in b:
        c=level2item["name"]
        categories_hierarchy.append([a,c,c,c])
        try:
            d = level2item["categories"]
            for level3item in d:
                e=level3item["name"]
                categories_hierarchy.append([a,c,e,e])
                try:
                    f = level3item["categories"]
                    for level4item in f:
                        g=level4item["name"]
                        categories_hierarchy.append([a,c,e,g])
                except:
                    pass
        except:
            pass

categories_hierarchy = pd.DataFrame(categories_hierarchy)
        
# sort the categories into three groups: 1) the competitors of the hypothetical business 2) the rest of the venues 3) not relevant

def create_categories(s):
    # for close competitors return the subcategory name
    if s[0] in ["Nightlife Spot"]:
        return [s[1],"Competitors"]
    # for most relevant categories return the subcategory name for each venue 
    elif s[0] in ["Arts & Entertainment", "Food", "Outdoors & Recreation"]:
        return [s[1],"Relevant, not competitor"]
    # for less relevant cagtegories return the parent category name for each venue
    elif s[0] in ["Professional & Other Places", "Event", "Shop & Service", "College & University"]:
        return [s[0],"Less relevant, not competitor"]
    # for non relevant categories, like residential and transport/travel
    else:
        return [s[0],"Not relevant"]

categories_hierarchy[['feature_selection','feature_relevancy']] = categories_hierarchy.apply(create_categories, axis=1, result_type="expand")
categories_hierarchy.set_index(3, inplace=True)

def lookup_features(s):
    try:
        return [ categories_hierarchy['feature_selection'][s['Venue Category']], categories_hierarchy['feature_relevancy'][s['Venue Category']] ]
    except:
        print(s['Venue Category'])
        return ["failed_to_get_category","Not relevant"]

# join the selected features to the venues dataframe and drop the rows with non-relevent venues

florence_venues_deduplicated[['feature_selection','feature_relevancy']] = florence_venues_deduplicated.apply(lookup_features, axis=1, result_type="expand")
florence_venues_deduplicated.drop(florence_venues_deduplicated[florence_venues_deduplicated['feature_relevancy'] == "Not relevant"].index, inplace=True)

# get details for venues

def get_venue_details(d):
    if d['feature_relevancy']=="Competitors":
        id = d['Venue ID']
        venue_url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/{}?client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}'.format(id, CLIENT_ID, CLIENT_SECRET, VERSION)
        result = requests.get(venue_url).json()
        try:
            likes = result['response']['venue']['likes']['count']
        except:
            likes = math.nan
        try:
            rating = result['response']['venue']['rating']
        except:
            rating = math.nan
        try:
            price_range = result['response']['venue']['price']['tier']
        except:
            price_range = math.nan
        try:
            visitors = result['response']['venue']['stats']['usersCount']
        except:
            visitors = math.nan
        try:
            visits = result['response']['venue']['stats']['visitsCount']
        except:
            visits = math.nan
        try:
            checkins = result['response']['venue']['stats']['checkinsCount']
        except:
            checkins = math.nan
        try:
            tips = result['response']['venue']['stats']['tipCount']
        except:
            tips = math.nan
        return [likes, rating, price_range, visitors, visits, checkins, tips]
    else:
        return [math.nan, math.nan, math.nan, math.nan, math.nan, math.nan, math.nan]
    
florence_venues_deduplicated[['venue_likes', 'venue_rating', 'venue_pricetier', 'venue_visitors', 'venue_visits', 'venue_checkins', 'venue_tips']] = florence_venues_deduplicated.apply(get_venue_details, axis=1, result_type="expand")

There are 24 neigborhood in Florence. The OSM database does not contain the boundaries as polygon for each of them but it has the geocoordinates for each neighborhood center. I collected these coordinates and defined a function that returns which of that is the closest to a given venue.

In [10]:
# get neighborhood name for each venue

florence_neighborhoods = ["Firenze Nova", "Poggetto", "Rifredi", "Romito", "Statuto", "Legnaia", "Monticelli", "Pignone", "Badia a Ripoli", "Bandino", "Gavinana", "Ricorboli", "San Marcellino", "Sorgane", "Bellariva", "Campo di Marte", "Coverciano", "Le Cure", "San Salvi", "Varlungo", "Oltrarno", "San Frediano", "San Iacopino", "San Niccolò"]
florence_neighborhood_lat=[]
florence_neighborhood_lon=[]

for nh in florence_neighborhoods:
    geojson_nh = requests.get('https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/search.php?q={}&polygon_geojson=1&format=geojson'.format(urllib.parse.quote("Florence, Italy, "+nh)))
    i=0
    while geojson_nh.json()['features'][i]['properties']['type'] != 'neighbourhood':
        i=i+1
    florence_neighborhood_lat.append(geojson_nh.json()['features'][i]['geometry']['coordinates'][0])
    florence_neighborhood_lon.append(geojson_nh.json()['features'][i]['geometry']['coordinates'][1])    
florence_neighborhoods2 = [florence_neighborhoods, florence_neighborhood_lat, florence_neighborhood_lon]

florence_neigborhoods_df = pd.DataFrame(florence_neighborhoods2).T

def cls(s):
    mindist=100000
    for i in range(0,len(florence_neigborhoods_df[1])):
        dist=geodesic((florence_neigborhoods_df[2][i],florence_neigborhoods_df[1][i]),(s['Venue Latitude'],s['Venue Longitude']))
        if dist < mindist:
            mindist=dist
            mindist_ind=i
        else:
            pass
    return florence_neigborhoods_df[0][mindist_ind]

florence_venues_deduplicated["Neighborhood"]=florence_venues_deduplicated.apply(cls,axis=1)
